<h2>The float of the Holy Christ of Mercy</h2>
<p>The <strong>mystery float</strong> of the Brotherhood of the Perdón in <strong>La Línea de la Concepción</strong> is the heart of the corporation’s penitential devotion on <strong>Maundy Thursday</strong>. It brings together neighbourhood faith and care for religious heritage: not only a sculptural group but a <strong>moving liturgical space</strong> where image, metalwork, fabric and light meet the silence of the streets and the pace of hooded penitents.</p>
<h2>The titular image and sculptural group</h2>
<p>The Christ, <strong>Jesus of Mercy in His Three Falls</strong>, is the work of the Seville sculptor <strong>Manuel Hernández León</strong>, blessed in <strong>February 1985</strong>, at a time of renewal for local cofrade life. The composition evokes the Lord’s way to Calvary with a tender reading of the fall and weariness borne out of love. The <strong>Cyrene</strong> and <strong>Holy Veronica</strong>, from the same workshop (<strong>1986</strong>), complete the mystery with stylistic unity and scale suited to the procession float.</p>
<h2>The float, gilding and artistic setting</h2>
<p>The <strong>float</strong>—platform and carriage—is designed to bear the group with dignity and to be seen in motion: balance between image, breathing space and base seeks both <strong>solemnity and clarity</strong> from the pavement. <strong>Poles</strong>, basket and metalwork serve practice and symbol together: they structure space, hold candles and vases when used, and add the restrained gleam typical of penitential taste. <strong>Embroidery</strong> on canopy or side hangings, when the brotherhood uses them, extends in cloth the colour scheme of the float and links sculpture and furnishings.</p>
<h2>The procession on Maundy Thursday</h2>
<p>During the <strong>penitential station</strong>, the Christ float moves to the rhythm of the <strong>bearer team</strong>, the anonymous heart of the brotherhood: gait, halts and cornering belong to popular ritual that turns the city route into a path of conversion. Music, prayer and the crowd’s respect shape a devotion that aims at <strong>recollection</strong>, not spectacle. Hence preparing the float—cleaning, checking furnishings, lighting and flowers—is shared work over many months at the brotherhood house and church.</p>
<h2>Conservation and living memory</h2>
<p>To care for the float is to guard living memory: every intervention needs technical judgement and theological sense, avoiding display that would betray the mystery’s simplicity. The Brotherhood, with <strong>St Peter’s parish</strong> and diocesan guidance, keeps the ensemble fit for worship and for the silent preaching of Holy Week streets. This page can be updated with restoration notes, new pieces or historic photographs through the administration panel so members and visitors have reliable information on the heritage of the Lord of Mercy in La Línea.</p>
